<content>
    <para id="eip-607">The average deviation from the mean (a.d.), also know as the Mean Absolute Deviation (M.A.D.), is used measure of central tendency of a set of data. 

</para><para id="fs-id1169030269244">It gives a more accurate measure of the central tendency than standard deviation for all life-like situations where small errors will occur in observation and measurement.</para>


    <para id="Trogdor"><link target-id="table1" strength="3"/> shows the absolute and
      squared deviations of the numbers 2, 3, 4, 9, and 16 from their
      their mean of 6.8. You can see that the average of
      absolute deviations from the mean (4.6). On the other hand,
      the average of squared deviations from the mean (27.0).
    </para><table id="table1" frame="all" summary="">
      <title>Absolute and squared deviations from the
	the mean of 6.8.</title>
      <tgroup cols="3" colsep="1" rowsep="1">
	<thead>
	  <row>
	    <entry>Value</entry>
	    <entry>Absolute Deviation from Median</entry>
	    <entry>Squared Deviation from Median</entry>
	  </row>
	</thead>
	<tbody>
	  <row>
	    <entry align="center">2</entry>
	    <entry align="center">4.8</entry>
	    <entry align="center">23.04</entry>
	  </row>
	  <row>
	    <entry align="center">3</entry>
	    <entry align="center">3.8</entry>
	    <entry align="center">14.44</entry>
	  </row>
	  <row>
	    <entry align="center">4</entry>
	    <entry align="center">2.8</entry>
	    <entry align="center">7.84</entry>
	  </row>
	  <row>
	    <entry align="center">9</entry>
	    <entry align="center">2.2</entry>
	    <entry align="center">4.84</entry>
	  </row>
	  <row>
	    <entry align="center">16</entry>
	    <entry align="center">9.2</entry>
	    <entry align="center">84.64</entry>
	  </row>
	  <row>
	    <entry align="center"><emphasis>Average</emphasis></entry>
	    <entry align="center"><emphasis>4.6</emphasis></entry>
	    <entry align="center"><emphasis>27.0</emphasis></entry>
	  </row>
	</tbody>
      </tgroup>
